Postman Interview Project¶

The data we have at hand has the following columns¶

Columns - ['transaction id', 'product id', 'product description', 'quantity sold', 'transaction timestamp', 'unit price', 'customer id', 'transaction country']

Some questions we want to answer looking at the data are¶

  • Is the company's performance improving or degrading over time?
  • Examine and highlight important trends visible in the sales data and insights.
  • How can we measure our performance in terms of customer acquisition and building customer loyalty?

Importing necessary libraries

  • numpy
  • pandas
  • matplotlib

Note : all libraries are open source libraries

Insights about data

  • The data provided in the form on the sales data has a total of 541909 entries.
  • Out of these 9288 entries are for cancelled transactions.
  • This leaves us with a total of 532621 entries.
  • Out of these 532621 entries, we are cleansing entries where the unit price or quantity sold was lesser than 0.
  • This leaves us with a total of 531283 entries , which pertain to 20726 unique transactions.

Insights¶

  • Evidently it can be seen that the company performed better with time with a high growth in the fall and winter months
  • The same can be accredited with festive season of Christmas and say Thanksgiving
  • Althuough with just one year of data, it may be said that the company performed better with time, it must be noted that our inference is limited by performance of corresponding months of different years.It can so happen that the festive season saw more buyers but not the other months.
  • To analyse if the company consistently performed better, we must look at data which spans a time of more than just a year to have a comparison of quarterly spending across different years.

Insights¶

  • The country level data helps us see that spikes in the expenditure occur at different times in different countries.
  • This may provide valuable insights to supply chain and logistics to prepare better for a heavy consumption season.
  • Spikes can be related to particular events occuring in that particular country at any point in time.

Customer Level¶

The following analysis is done on customer level to find out the different customers who may be loyal customers to the store. This will help the store determine its customer retention policies.

In [47]:
grouped_df = df.groupby(['customer id'])['transaction timestamp'].unique().reset_index()
grouped_df=grouped_df.set_index('customer id')
grouped_df.index = grouped_df.index.astype('int64')
In [48]:
grouped_df['number of transactions']  = grouped_df["transaction timestamp"].apply(lambda x: len(x))
grouped_df['number of transactions'].mean()
Out[48]:
4.2507490205116385

It is evident that the average number of transactions per customer in the data i.e., in a period of one year is 4.25

Let us try to explore the number of customers who have a beyond average spending/transaction habit.

In [49]:
grouped_df.shape[0],grouped_df[grouped_df['number of transactions'] > grouped_df['number of transactions'].mean()].shape[0]
Out[49]:
(4339, 1112)

The database contains a total of 4339 unique customers out of which 1112 customers can be labelled loyal customers for the store. It can also be inferred that the loyal customers for the store visit it atleast 5 times during a period of one year.

However, to undoubtedly deduce the same would be naive, since a customer could make 5 different transactions in a single day and then not make purchases on different days

In [50]:
grouped_df=grouped_df[grouped_df['number of transactions'] > grouped_df['number of transactions'].mean()]
x = grouped_df['transaction timestamp'].apply(lambda x: np.diff(x).mean())
grouped_df['mean_of_difference_between_transactions'] = x
In [51]:
for i, row in grouped_df.iterrows():
    day = grouped_df.at[i,'mean_of_difference_between_transactions'].days
    grouped_df.at[i,'mean_of_difference_between_transactions_day'] = day
grouped_df.drop('mean_of_difference_between_transactions',axis=1,inplace=True)
grouped_df.rename(columns={"mean_of_difference_between_transactions_day": "mean_of_difference_between_transactions"},inplace=True)
In [52]:
grouped_df['mean_of_difference_between_transactions'].mean()
Out[52]:
39.57464028776978
In [53]:
grouped_df.shape[0],grouped_df[grouped_df['mean_of_difference_between_transactions'] > grouped_df['mean_of_difference_between_transactions'].mean()].shape[0]
Out[53]:
(1112, 525)

Again, looking the 1112 customers that had more than average number of transactions i.e., 4.25 5, we find only 525 had a mean difference between transaction dates greater than 40 days.

This essentially means that 525 customers out of the total 4339 customers, can be labelled loyal customers, with a sense of surety that these customers visit stores regularly i.e., they visit the store after about 40 days.

Product Level¶

Let us determine the most popular products by quantity sold.
This data will help stores stock in adequate quantity and also look for products similar to popular products

In [55]:
grouped_df = df.groupby(['product id'])['quantity sold'].sum().reset_index()
grouped_df=grouped_df.set_index('product id')
In [56]:
grouped_df.sort_values('quantity sold',ascending=False,inplace=True, kind='quicksort')
In [57]:
grouped_df_2 = df.groupby(['product id'])['product description'].unique().reset_index()
grouped_df_2 = grouped_df_2.set_index('product id')
grouped_df_2['product description'] =  grouped_df_2['product description'].apply(lambda x : x[0])
grouped_df = pd.merge(grouped_df, grouped_df_2, left_on='product id',right_on='product id',how='outer',suffixes=('_left','_right'))
